# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hardware-accelerator-design
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/ai-accelerator] NPU can be standalone, a part of a CPU or a part of a GPU.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/ai-accelerator] Their purpose is either to efficiently execute already trained AI models (inference) or to train AI models.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/ai-accelerator] NPUs can be more efficient in terms of speed or power consumption.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/ai-accelerator] NPU applications include algorithms for robotics, Internet of things, and data-intensive or sensor-driven tasks.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/ai-accelerator] They are often manycore or spatial designs and focus on low-precision arithmetic, novel dataflow architectures, or in-memory computing capability.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/ai-accelerator] As of 2024, a widely used datacenter-grade AI integrated circuit chip, the Nvidia H100 GPU, contains tens of billions of MOSFETs.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/ai-accelerator] AI accelerators are used in Apple silicon, Qualcomm, Samsung, Huawei, and Google Tensor smartphone processors.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/ai-accelerator] Vision processing units are accelerators specialized for machine vision algorithms such as CNN (convolutional neural networks) and SIFT (scale-invariant feature transform).
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/ai-accelerator] They are used in devices that need to keep track of objects visually such as AR headsets and drones.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/ai-accelerator] It is more recently (circa 2017) added to processors from Apple and (circa 2022) to processors from Intel and AMD.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/ai-accelerator] All models of Intel Meteor Lake processors have a built-in *versatile processor unit* (*VPU*) for accelerating inference for computer vision and deep learning.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/ai-accelerator] On consumer devices, the NPU is intended to be small, power-efficient, but reasonably fast when used to run small models.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/ai-accelerator] To do this they are designed to support low-bitwidth operations using data types such as INT4, INT8, FP8, and FP16.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/ai-accelerator] A common metric is trillions of operations per second (TOPS).
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/ai-accelerator] Although TOPS does not explicitly specify the kind of operations, it is typically INT8 additions and multiplications.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/ai-accelerator] Accelerators are used in cloud computing servers: e.g., tensor processing units (TPU) for Google Cloud Platform, and Trainium and Inferentia chips for Amazon Web Services.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/ai-accelerator] Many vendor-specific terms exist for devices in this category, and it is an emerging technology without a dominant design.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/ai-accelerator] Since the late 2010s, graphics processing units designed by companies such as Nvidia and AMD often include AI-specific hardware in the form of dedicated functional units for low-precision matrix-multiplication operations.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/ai-accelerator] These GPUs are commonly used as AI accelerators, both for training and inference.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/ai-accelerator] Although NPUs are tailored for low-precision (e.g., FP16, INT8) matrix multiplication operations, they can be used to emulate higher-precision matrix multiplications in scientific computing.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/ai-accelerator] As modern GPUs place much focus on making the NPU part fast, using emulated FP64 (Ozaki scheme) on NPUs can potentially outperform native FP64.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/ai-accelerator] This has been demonstrated using FP16-emulated FP64 on NVIDIA TITAN RTX and using INT8-emulated FP64 on NVIDIA consumer GPUs and the A100 GPU.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/ai-accelerator] Consumer GPUs especially benefited as they have limited FP64 hardware capacity, showing a 6× speedup.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/ai-accelerator] Since CUDA Toolkit 13.0 Update 2, cuBLAS automatically uses INT8-emulated FP64 matrix multiplication of the equivalent precision if it is faster than native.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/ai-accelerator] This is in addition to the FP16-emulated FP32 feature introduced in version 12.9.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/ai-accelerator] An operating system or a higher-level library may provide application programming interfaces such as TensorFlow with LiteRT Next (Android), CoreML (iOS, macOS) or DirectML (Windows).
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/ai-accelerator] Formats such as ONNX are used to represent trained neural networks.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/ai-accelerator] Consumer CPU-integrated NPUs are accessible through vendor-specific APIs.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/ai-accelerator] AMD (Ryzen AI), Intel (OpenVINO), Apple silicon (CoreML), and Qualcomm (SNPE) each have their own APIs, which can be built upon by a higher-level library.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/ai-accelerator] GPUs generally use existing GPGPU pipelines such as CUDA and OpenCL adapted for lower precisions and specialized matrix-multiplication operations.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/ai-accelerator] Custom-built systems such as the Google TPU use private interfaces.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/ai-accelerator] There are a large number of separate underlying acceleration APIs and compilers/runtimes in use in the AI field, causing a great increase in software development effort due to the many combinations involved.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/ai-accelerator] As of 2025, the open standard organization Khronos Group is pursuing standardization of AI-related interfaces to reduce the amount of work needed.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/ai-accelerator] Khronos is working on three separate fronts: expansion of data types and intrinsic operations in OpenCL and Vulkan, inclusion of compute graphs in SPIR-V, and a NNEF/SkriptND file format for describing a neural network.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/application-specific-instruction-set-processor] An **application-specific instruction set processor** (**ASIP**) is a component used in system on a chip design.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/application-specific-instruction-set-processor] The instruction set architecture of an ASIP is tailored to benefit a specific application.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/application-specific-instruction-set-processor] This specialization of the core provides a tradeoff between the flexibility of a general purpose central processing unit (CPU) and the performance of an application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC).
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/application-specific-instruction-set-processor] Some ASIPs have a configurable instruction set.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/application-specific-instruction-set-processor] Usually, these cores are divided into two parts: *static* logic which defines a minimum ISA (instruction-set architecture) and *configurable* logic which can be used to design new instructions.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/application-specific-instruction-set-processor] The configurable logic can be programmed either in the field in a similar fashion to a field-programmable gate array (FPGA) or during the chip synthesis.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/application-specific-instruction-set-processor] ASIPs have two ways of generating code: either through a retargetable code generator or through a retargetable compiler generator.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/application-specific-instruction-set-processor] The retargetable code generator uses the application, ISA, and Architecture Template to create the code generator for the object code.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/application-specific-instruction-set-processor] The retargetable compiler generator uses only the ISA and Architecture Template as the basis for creating the compiler.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/application-specific-instruction-set-processor] The application code will then be used by the compiler to create the object code.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/application-specific-instruction-set-processor] ASIPs can be used as an alternative to hardware accelerators for baseband signal processing or video coding.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/application-specific-instruction-set-processor] Traditional hardware accelerators for these applications suffer from inflexibility.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/application-specific-instruction-set-processor] It is very difficult to reuse the hardware datapath with handwritten finite-state machines (FSM).
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/application-specific-instruction-set-processor] The retargetable compilers of ASIPs help the designer to update the program and reuse the datapath.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/application-specific-instruction-set-processor] Typically, the ASIP design is more or less dependent on the tool flow because designing a processor from scratch can be very complicated.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/application-specific-instruction-set-processor] One approach is to describe the processor using a high level language and then to automatically generate the ASIP's software toolset.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/application-specific-instruction-set-processor] RISC-V Instruction Set Architecture (ISA) provides minimum base instruction sets that can be extended with additional application-specific instructions.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/application-specific-instruction-set-processor] The base instruction sets provide simplified control flow, memory and arithmetic operations on registers.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/application-specific-instruction-set-processor] Its modular design allows the base instructions to be extended for standard application-specific operations such as integer multiplication/division (M), single-precision floating point (F), or bit manipulation (B).
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/application-specific-instruction-set-processor] For the non-standard instruction extensions, encoding space of the ISA is divided into three parts: *standard, reserverd,* and *custom.* The *custom* encoding space is used for vendor-specific extensions.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] A **coprocessor** is a computer processor used to supplement the functions of the primary processor (the CPU).
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] Operations performed by the coprocessor may be floating-point arithmetic, graphics, signal processing, string processing, cryptography or I/O interfacing with peripheral devices.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] By offloading processor-intensive tasks from the main processor, coprocessors can accelerate system performance.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] Coprocessors allow a line of computers to be customized, so that customers who do not need the extra performance do not need to pay for it.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] Coprocessors vary in their degree of autonomy.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] Some (such as FPUs) rely on direct control via coprocessor instructions, embedded in the CPU's instruction stream.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] Others are independent processors in their own right, capable of working asynchronously; they are still not optimized for general-purpose code, or they are incapable of it due to a limited instruction set focused on accelerating specific tasks.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] It is common for these to be driven by direct memory access (DMA), with the host processor (a CPU) building a command list.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] The PlayStation 2's Emotion Engine contained an unusual DSP-like SIMD vector unit capable of both modes of operation.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] To make the best use of mainframe computer processor time, input/output tasks were delegated to separate systems called Channel I/O.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] The mainframe would not require any I/O processing at all, instead, it would set parameters for an input or output operation and then signal the channel processor to carry out the whole of the operation.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] By dedicating relatively simple sub-processors to handle time-consuming I/O formatting and processing, overall system performance was improved.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] Coprocessors for floating-point arithmetic first appeared in desktop computers in the 1970s and became common throughout the 1980s and into the early 1990s.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] Early 8-bit and 16-bit processors used software to carry out floating-point arithmetic operations.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] Where a coprocessor was supported, floating-point calculations could be carried out many times faster.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] Math coprocessors were popular purchases for users of computer-aided design (CAD) software and scientific and engineering calculations.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] Some floating-point units, such as the AMD 9511, Intel 8231/8232 and Weitek FPUs were treated as peripheral devices, while others such as the Intel 8087, Motorola 68881 and National 32081 were more closely integrated with the CPU.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] Another form of coprocessor was a video display coprocessor, as used in the Atari 8-bit computers, TI-99/4A, and MSX home computers, which were called "Video Display Controllers".
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] The Amiga custom chipset includes such a unit known as the Copper, as well as a blitter for accelerating bitmap manipulation in memory.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] As microprocessors developed, the cost of integrating the floating-point arithmetic functions into the processor declined.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] High processor speeds also made a closely integrated coprocessor difficult to implement.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] Separately packaged mathematics coprocessors are now uncommon in desktop computers.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] The demand for a dedicated graphics coprocessor has grown, however, particularly due to the increasing demand for realistic 3D graphics in computer games.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] The original IBM PC included a socket for the Intel 8087 floating-point coprocessor (aka FPU) which was a popular option for people using the PC for computer-aided design or mathematics-intensive calculations.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] In that architecture, the coprocessor speeds up floating-point arithmetic on the order of fiftyfold.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] Users that only used the PC for word processing, for example, saved the high cost of the coprocessor, which would not have accelerated performance of text manipulation operations.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] The 8087 was tightly integrated with the 8086/8088 and responded to floating-point machine code operation codes inserted in the 8088 instruction stream.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] An 8088 processor without an 8087 could not interpret these instructions, requiring separate versions of programs for FPU and non-FPU systems, or at least a test at run time to detect the FPU and select appropriate mathematical library functions.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] Another coprocessor for the 8086/8088 central processor was the 8089 input/output coprocessor.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] It used the same programming technique as 8087 for input/output operations, such as transfer of data from memory to a peripheral device, and so reducing the load on the CPU.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] But IBM did not use it in IBM PC design and Intel stopped development of this type of coprocessor.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] The Intel 80386 microprocessor used an optional "math" coprocessor (the 80387) to perform floating-point operations directly in hardware.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] The Intel 80486DX processor included floating-point hardware on the chip.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] Intel released a cost-reduced processor, the 80486SX, that had no floating-point hardware, and also sold an 80487SX coprocessor that essentially disabled the main processor when installed, since the 80487SX was a complete 80486DX with a different set of pin connections.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] Intel processors later than the 80486 integrated floating-point hardware on the main processor chip; the advances in integration eliminated the cost advantage of selling the floating-point processor as an optional element.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] It would be very difficult to adapt circuit-board techniques adequate at 75 MHz processor speed to meet the time-delay, power consumption, and radio-frequency interference standards required at gigahertz-range clock speeds.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] These on-chip floating-point processors are still referred to as coprocessors because they operate in parallel with the main CPU.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] During the era of 8- and 16-bit desktop computers another common source of floating-point coprocessors was Weitek.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] These coprocessors had a different instruction set from the Intel coprocessors, and used a different socket, which not all motherboards supported.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] The Weitek processors did not provide transcendental mathematics functions (for example, trigonometric functions) like the Intel x87 family, and required specific software libraries to support their functions.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] The Motorola 68000 family had the 68881/68882 coprocessors which provided similar floating-point speed acceleration as for the Intel processors.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] Computers using the 68000 family but not equipped with the hardware floating-point processor could trap and emulate the floating-point instructions in software, which, although slower, allowed one binary version of the program to be distributed for both cases.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] The 68451 memory-management coprocessor was designed to work with the 68020 processor.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] As of 2001, dedicated Graphics Processing Units (GPUs) in the form of graphics cards are commonplace.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] In 2006, AGEIA announced an add-in card for computers that it called the PhysX PPU.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] PhysX was designed to perform complex physics computations so that the CPU and GPU do not have to perform these time-consuming calculations.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] It was designed for video games, although other mathematical uses could theoretically be developed for it.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] In 2008, Nvidia purchased the company and phased out the PhysX card line; the functionality was added through software allowing their GPUs to render PhysX on cores normally used for graphics processing, using their Nvidia PhysX engine software.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] In 2006, BigFoot Systems unveiled a PCI add-in card they christened the KillerNIC which ran its own special Linux kernel on a FreeScale PowerQUICC running at 400 MHz, calling the FreeScale chip a Network Processing Unit or NPU.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] The SpursEngine is a media-oriented add-in card with a coprocessor based on the Cell microarchitecture.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] The SPUs are themselves vector coprocessors.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] In 2008, Khronos Group released the OpenCL with the aim to support general-purpose CPUs, ATI/AMD and Nvidia GPUs (and other accelerators) with a single common language for compute kernels.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] In 2010s, some mobile computation devices had implemented the sensor hub as a coprocessor.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] Examples of coprocessors used for handling sensor integration in mobile devices include the Apple M7 and M8 motion coprocessors, the Qualcomm Snapdragon Sensor Core and Qualcomm Hexagon, and the Holographic Processing Unit for the Microsoft HoloLens.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] In 2012, Intel announced the Intel Xeon Phi coprocessor.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] Over time CPUs have tended to grow to absorb the functionality of the most popular coprocessors.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] FPUs are now considered an integral part of a processors' main pipeline; SIMD units gave multimedia its acceleration, taking over the role of various DSP accelerator cards; and even GPUs have become integrated on CPU dies.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/coprocessor] Nonetheless, specialized units remain popular away from desktop machines, and for additional power, and allow continued evolution independently of the main processor product lines.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] A **digital signal processor** (**DSP**) is a specialized microprocessor chip, with its architecture optimized for the operational needs of digital signal processing.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] DSPs are fabricated on metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) integrated circuit chips.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] They are widely used in audio signal processing, telecommunications, digital image processing, radar, sonar and speech recognition systems, and in common consumer electronic devices such as mobile phones, disk drives and high-definition television (HDTV) products.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] The goal of a DSP is usually to measure, filter or compress continuous real-world analog signals.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] Most general-purpose microprocessors can also execute digital signal processing algorithms successfully, but may not be able to keep up with such processing continuously in real-time.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] Also, dedicated DSPs usually have better power efficiency, thus they are more suitable in portable devices such as mobile phones because of power consumption constraints.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] DSPs often use special memory architectures that are able to fetch multiple data or instructions at the same time.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] Digital signal processing (DSP) algorithms typically require a large number of mathematical operations to be performed quickly and repeatedly on a series of data samples.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] Signals (perhaps from audio or video sensors) are constantly converted from analog to digital, manipulated digitally, and then converted back to analog form.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] Many DSP applications have constraints on latency; that is, for the system to work, the DSP operation must be completed within some fixed time, and deferred (or batch) processing is not viable.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] Most general-purpose microprocessors and operating systems can execute DSP algorithms successfully, but are not suitable for use in portable devices such as mobile phones and PDAs because of power efficiency constraints.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] A specialized DSP, however, will tend to provide a lower-cost solution, with better performance, lower latency, and no requirements for specialised cooling or large batteries.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] For example, the SES-12 and SES-14 satellites from operator SES launched in 2018, were both built by Airbus Defence and Space with 25% of capacity using DSP.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] The architecture of a DSP is optimized specifically for digital signal processing.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] Most also support some of the features of an applications processor or microcontroller, since signal processing is rarely the only task of a system.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] Some useful features for optimizing DSP algorithms are outlined below.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] Both traditional and DSP-optimized instruction sets are able to compute any arbitrary operation but an operation that might require multiple ARM or x86 instructions to compute might require only one instruction in a DSP-optimized instruction set.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] One implication for software architecture is that hand-optimized assembly-code routines (assembly programs) are commonly packaged into libraries for re-use, instead of relying on advanced compiler technologies to handle essential algorithms.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] Even with modern compiler optimizations, hand-optimized assembly code is more efficient, and many common algorithms involved in DSP calculations are hand-written in order to take full advantage of the architectural optimizations.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] DSPs can sometimes rely on supporting code to know about cache hierarchies and the associated delays.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] This is a tradeoff that allows for better performance.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] In addition, extensive use of DMA is employed.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] DSPs frequently use multi-tasking operating systems, but have no support for virtual memory or memory protection.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] Operating systems that use virtual memory require more time for context switching among processes, which increases latency.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] In 1976, Richard Wiggins proposed the Speak & Spell concept to Paul Breedlove, Larry Brantingham, and Gene Frantz at Texas Instruments' Dallas research facility.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] Two years later in 1978, they produced the first Speak & Spell, with the technological centerpiece being the TMS5100, the industry's first digital signal processor.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] It also set other milestones, being the first chip to use linear predictive coding to perform speech synthesis.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] The chip was made possible with a 7 μm PMOS fabrication process.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] In 1978, American Microsystems (AMI) released the S2811.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] The AMI S2811 "signal processing peripheral", like many later DSPs, has a hardware multiplier that enables it to do multiply–accumulate operation in a single instruction.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] The S2811 was the first integrated circuit chip specifically designed as a DSP, and fabricated using vertical metal oxide semiconductor (VMOS, V-groove MOS), a technology that had previously not been mass-produced.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] It was designed as a microprocessor peripheral, for the Motorola 6800, and it had to be initialized by the host.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] The S2811 was not successful in the market.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] In 1979, Intel released the 2920 as an "analog signal processor".
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] It had an on-chip ADC/DAC with an internal signal processor, but it didn't have a hardware multiplier and was not successful in the market.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] In 1980, the first stand-alone complete DSPs, the NEC μPD7720, based on the modified Harvard architecture and AT&T's DSP1 – were presented at the International Solid-State Circuits Conference '80.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] Both processors were inspired by the research in public switched telephone network (PSTN) telecommunications.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] The μPD7720, introduced for voiceband applications, was one of the most commercially successful early DSPs.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] The Altamira DX-1 was another early DSP, utilizing quad integer pipelines with delayed branches and branch prediction.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] Another DSP produced by Texas Instruments (TI), the TMS32010, presented in 1983, proved to be an even bigger success.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] It was based on the Harvard architecture, and so had separate instruction and data memory.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] It already had a special instruction set, with instructions like load-and-accumulate or multiply-and-accumulate.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] It could work on 16-bit numbers and needed 390 ns for a multiply–add operation.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] TI is now the market leader in general-purpose DSPs.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] About five years later, the second generation of DSPs began to spread.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] They had 3 memories for storing two operands simultaneously and included hardware to accelerate tight loops; they also had an addressing unit capable of loop-addressing.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] Some of them operated on 24-bit variables, and a typical model only required about 21 ns for a MAC.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] Members of this generation were, for example, the AT&T DSP16A or the Motorola 56000.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] The main improvement in the third generation was the appearance of application-specific units and instructions in the data path, or sometimes as coprocessors.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] These units allowed direct hardware acceleration of very specific but complex mathematical problems, like the Fourier transform or matrix operations.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] Some chips, like the Motorola MC68356, even included more than one processor core to work in parallel.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] Other DSPs from 1995 are the TI TMS320C541 or the TMS320C80.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] The fourth generation is best characterized by the changes in the instruction set and the instruction encoding/decoding.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] SIMD extensions were added, and VLIW and the superscalar architecture appeared.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] As always, the clock speeds have increased; a 3 ns MAC now became possible.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] Modern signal processors yield greater performance; this is due in part to both technological and architectural advancements like lower design rules, fast-access two-level cache, (E)DMA circuitry, and a wider bus system.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] Not all DSPs provide the same speed and many kinds of signal processors exist, each one of them being better suited for a specific task, ranging in price from about US$1.50 to US$300.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] Texas Instruments produces the C6000 series DSPs, which have clock speeds of 1.2 GHz and implement separate instruction and data caches.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] They also have an 8 MiB 2nd level cache and 64 EDMA channels.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] The top models are capable of as many as 8000 MIPS (millions of instructions per second), use VLIW (very long instruction word), perform eight operations per clock-cycle and are compatible with a broad range of external peripherals and various buses (PCI/serial/etc).
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] TMS320C6474 chips each have three such DSPs, and the newest generation C6000 chips support floating point as well as fixed point processing.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] Freescale produces a multi-core DSP family, the MSC81xx.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] The MSC81xx is based on StarCore Architecture processors and the latest MSC8144 DSP combines four programmable SC3400 StarCore DSP cores.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] Each SC3400 StarCore DSP core has a clock speed of 1 GHz.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] XMOS produces a multi-core multi-threaded line of processors well suited to DSP operations.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] They come in various speeds ranging from 400 to 1600 MIPS.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] The processors have a multi-threaded architecture that allows up to 8 real-time threads per core, meaning that a 4-core device would support up to 32 real-time threads.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] Threads communicate with each other through buffered channels that are capable of up to 80 Mbit/s.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] CEVA, Inc. produces and licenses three distinct families of DSPs.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] Perhaps the best known and most widely deployed is the CEVA-TeakLite DSP family, a classic memory-based architecture, with 16-bit or 32-bit word-widths and single or dual MACs.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] The CEVA-X DSP family offers a combination of VLIW and SIMD architectures, with different members of the family offering dual or quad 16-bit MACs.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] The CEVA-XC DSP family targets software-defined radio (SDR) modem designs and leverages a unique combination of VLIW and Vector architectures with 32 16-bit MACs.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] Analog Devices produce the SHARC-based DSP and range in performance from 66 MHz/198 MFLOPS (million floating-point operations per second) to 400 MHz/2400 MFLOPS.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] Some models support multiple multipliers and ALUs, SIMD instructions and audio processing-specific components and peripherals.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] The Blackfin family of embedded digital signal processors combines the features of a DSP with those of a general-purpose processor.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] As a result, these processors can run simple operating systems like μCLinux, Velocity and Nucleus RTOS while operating on real-time data.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] The SHARC-based ADSP-210xx provides both delayed branches and non-delayed branches.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] NXP Semiconductors produce DSPs based on TriMedia VLIW technology, optimized for audio and video processing.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] In some products, the DSP core is hidden as a fixed-function block in a SoC, but NXP also provides a range of flexible single-core media processors.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] The TriMedia media processors support both fixed-point arithmetic as well as floating-point arithmetic, and have specific instructions to deal with complex filters and entropy coding.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] CSR produces the Quatro family of SoCs that contain one or more custom Imaging DSPs optimized for processing document image data for scanner and copier applications.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] Microchip Technology produces the PIC24 based dsPIC line of DSPs.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] Introduced in 2004, the dsPIC is designed for applications needing a true DSP as well as a true microcontroller, such as motor control and in power supplies.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] The dsPIC runs at up to 40MIPS, and has support for 16-bit fixed-point MAC, bit reverse and modulo addressing, as well as DMA.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] Most DSPs use fixed-point arithmetic because, in real-world signal processing, the additional range provided by floating point is not needed, and there is a large speed and cost benefit due to reduced hardware complexity.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] Floating-point DSPs may be invaluable in applications where a wide dynamic range is required.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] Product developers might also use floating-point DSPs to reduce the cost and complexity of software development in exchange for more expensive hardware, since it is generally easier to implement algorithms in floating point.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] Generally, DSPs are dedicated integrated circuits; however, DSP functionality can also be produced by using field-programmable gate array chips (FPGAs).
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] Embedded general-purpose RISC processors are becoming increasingly DSP-like in functionality.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] For example, the OMAP3 processors include an ARM Cortex-A8 and C6000 DSP.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] In communications, a new breed of DSPs offering the fusion of both DSP functions and hardware acceleration functions is making its way into the mainstream.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] Such Modem processors include ASOCS ModemX and CEVA's XC4000.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] In May 2018, Huarui-2 designed by Nanjing Research Institute of Electronics Technology of China Electronics Technology Group passed acceptance.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] With a processing speed of 0.4 TFLOPS, the chip can achieve better performance than current mainstream DSP chips.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] The design team has begun to create Huarui-3, which has a processing speed in TFLOPS level and support for artificial intelligence.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] An example of such an IC is the Silicon Labs/Skyworks Si4831/35 series, which supports both FM and AM decoding within a single chip.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] Many such ICs (including the Si4831/35 above) are suitable for use with – and designed for – externally traditional, mechanically-tuned designs.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/digital-signal-processor] Compared to traditional true analog circuitry, these may exhibit noticeable tuning and audio idiosyncracies (e.g., tuning jumping in discrete steps rather than continuously), particularly with older DSP-based designs.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] A **field-programmable gate array** (**FPGA**) is a type of configurable integrated circuit that can be repeatedly programmed after manufacturing.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] FPGAs are a subset of logic devices referred to as programmable logic devices (PLDs).
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] They consist of a grid-connected array of programmable logic blocks that can be configured "in the field" to interconnect with other logic blocks to perform various digital functions.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] FPGAs are often used in limited (low) quantity production of custom-made products, and in research and development, where the higher cost of individual FPGAs is not as important and where creating and manufacturing a custom circuit would not be feasible.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Other applications for FPGAs include the telecommunications, automotive, aerospace, and industrial sectors, which benefit from their flexibility, high signal processing speed, and parallel processing abilities.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] An FPGA configuration is generally written using a hardware description language (HDL), e.g., VHDL, similar to the ones used for application-specific integrated circuits (ASICs).
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Circuit diagrams were formerly used to write the configuration.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] The logic blocks of an FPGA can be configured to perform complex combinational functions, or act as simple logic gates like AND and XOR.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] In most FPGAs, logic blocks also include memory elements, which may be simple flip-flops or more sophisticated blocks of memory.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Many FPGAs can be reprogrammed to implement different logic functions, allowing flexible reconfigurable computing as performed in computer software.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] FPGAs are also commonly used during the development of ASICs to speed up the simulation process.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] The FPGA industry sprouted from programmable read-only memory (PROM) and programmable logic devices (PLDs).
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] PROMs and PLDs both had the option of being programmed in batches in a factory or in the field (field-programmable).
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Altera was founded in 1983 and delivered the industry's first reprogrammable logic device in 1984 – the EP300 – which featured a quartz window in the package that allowed users to shine an ultraviolet lamp on the die to erase the EPROM cells that held the device configuration.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Xilinx (now owned by AMD) produced the first commercially viable field-programmable gate array in 1985 – the XC2064.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] The XC2064 had programmable gates and programmable interconnects between gates, the beginnings of a new technology and market.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] The XC2064 had 64 configurable logic blocks (CLBs), with two three-input lookup tables (LUTs).
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] In 1987, the Naval Surface Warfare Center funded an experiment proposed by Steve Casselman to develop a computer that would implement 600,000 reprogrammable gates.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Casselman was successful and a patent related to the system was issued in 1992.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Altera and Xilinx continued unchallenged and quickly grew from 1985 to the mid-1990s when competitors sprouted up, eroding a significant portion of their market share.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] By 1993, Actel (later Microsemi, now Microchip) was serving about 18 percent of the market.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] The 1990s were a period of rapid growth for FPGAs, both in circuit sophistication and the volume of production.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] In the early 1990s, FPGAs were primarily used in telecommunications and networking.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] By the end of the decade, FPGAs found their way into consumer, automotive, and industrial applications.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] By 2013, Altera (31 percent), Xilinx (36 percent), and Actel (10 percent) together represented approximately 77 percent of the FPGA market.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Companies like Microsoft have started to use FPGAs to accelerate high-performance, computationally intensive systems (like the data centers that operate their Bing search engine), due to the performance per watt advantage FPGAs deliver.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Microsoft began using FPGAs to accelerate Bing in 2014, and in 2018 began deploying FPGAs across other data center workloads for their Azure cloud computing platform.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Since 2019, modern generations of FPGAs have been integrated with other architectures like AI engines to target workloads in the artificial intelligence domain.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] The following timelines indicate progress in different aspects of FPGA design.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] A *design start* is a new custom design for implementation on an FPGA.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Contemporary FPGAs have ample logic gates and RAM blocks to implement complex digital computations.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] FPGAs can be used to implement any logical function that an ASIC can perform.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] The ability to update the functionality after shipping, partial re-configuration of a portion of the design and the low non-recurring engineering costs relative to an ASIC design (notwithstanding the generally higher unit cost), offer advantages for many applications.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] As FPGA designs employ very fast I/O rates and bidirectional data buses, it becomes a challenge to verify correct timing of valid data within setup time and hold time.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Floor planning helps resource allocation within FPGAs to meet these timing constraints.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Some FPGAs have analog features in addition to digital functions.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] The most common analog feature is a programmable slew rate on each output pin.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] This allows the user to set low rates on lightly loaded pins that would otherwise ring or couple unacceptably, and to set higher rates on heavily loaded high-speed channels that would otherwise run too slowly.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Also common are quartz-crystal oscillator driver circuitry, on-chip RC oscillators, and phase-locked loops with embedded voltage-controlled oscillators used for clock generation and management as well as for high-speed serializer and deserializer (SERDES) transmit clocks and receiver clock recovery.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Fairly common are differential comparators on input pins designed to be connected to differential signaling channels.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] A few mixed-signal FPGAs have integrated peripheral analog-to-digital converters (ADCs) and digital-to-analog converters (DACs) with analog signal conditioning blocks, allowing them to operate as a system on a chip (SoC).
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Such devices blur the line between an FPGA, which carries digital ones and zeros on its internal programmable interconnect fabric, and field-programmable analog array (FPAA), which carries analog values on its internal programmable interconnect fabric.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] The most common FPGA architecture consists of an array of logic blocks called configurable logic blocks (CLBs) or logic array blocks (LABs) (depending on vendor), I/O pads, and routing channels.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Generally, all the routing channels have the same width (number of signals).
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Multiple I/O pads may fit into the height of one row or the width of one column in the array.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] "An application circuit must be mapped into an FPGA with adequate resources.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] While the number of logic blocks and I/Os required is easily determined from the design, the number of routing channels needed may vary considerably even among designs with the same amount of logic.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] For example, a crossbar switch requires much more routing than a systolic array with the same gate count.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Since unused routing channels increase the cost (and decrease the performance) of the FPGA without providing any benefit, FPGA manufacturers try to provide just enough channels so that most designs that will fit in terms of lookup tables (LUTs) and I/Os can be routed.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] In general, a logic block consists of a few logical cells.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] A typical cell consists of a 4-input LUT, a full adder (FA) and a D-type flip-flop.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] The LUT might be split into two 3-input LUTs.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] In *normal mode* those are combined into a 4-input LUT through the first multiplexer (mux).
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] In *arithmetic* mode, their outputs are fed to the adder.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] The selection of mode is programmed into the second mux.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] The output can be either synchronous or asynchronous, depending on the programming of the third mux.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] In practice, the entire adder or parts of it are stored as functions into the LUTs in order to save space.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Modern FPGA families expand upon the above capabilities to include higher-level functionality fixed in silicon.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Having these common functions embedded in the circuit reduces the area required and gives those functions increased performance compared to building them from logical primitives.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Examples of these include multipliers, generic DSP blocks, embedded processors, high-speed I/O logic and embedded memories.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Higher-end FPGAs can contain high-speed multi-gigabit transceivers and *hard IP cores* such as processor cores, Ethernet medium access control units, PCI or PCI Express controllers, and external memory controllers.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] These cores exist alongside the programmable fabric, but they are built out of transistors instead of LUTs so they have ASIC-level performance and power consumption without consuming a significant amount of fabric resources, leaving more of the fabric free for the application-specific logic.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] The multi-gigabit transceivers also contain high-performance signal conditioning circuitry along with high-speed serializers and deserializers, components that cannot be built out of LUTs.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Higher-level physical layer (PHY) functionality such as line coding may or may not be implemented alongside the serializers and deserializers in hard logic, depending on the FPGA.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] An alternate approach to using hard macro processors is to make use of soft processor IP cores that are implemented within the FPGA logic.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Nios II, MicroBlaze and Mico32 are examples of popular softcore processors.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Many modern FPGAs are programmed at *run time*, which has led to the idea of reconfigurable computing or reconfigurable systems – CPUs that reconfigure themselves to suit the task at hand.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Additionally, new non-FPGA architectures are beginning to emerge.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Software-configurable microprocessors such as the Stretch S5000 adopt a hybrid approach by providing an array of processor cores and FPGA-like programmable cores on the same chip.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] In 2012 the coarse-grained architectural approach was taken a step further by combining the logic blocks and interconnects of traditional FPGAs with embedded microprocessors and related peripherals to form a complete system on a programmable chip.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Examples of such hybrid technologies can be found in the Xilinx Zynq-7000 all programmable SoC, which includes a 1.0 GHz dual-core ARM Cortex-A9 MPCore processor embedded within the FPGA's logic fabric, or in the Altera Arria V FPGA, which includes an 800 MHz dual-core ARM Cortex-A9 MPCore.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] The Atmel FPSLIC is another such device, which uses an AVR processor in combination with Atmel's programmable logic architecture.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] The Microsemi SmartFusion devices incorporate an ARM Cortex-M3 hard processor core (with up to 512 kB of flash and 64 kB of RAM) and analog peripherals such as a multi-channel analog-to-digital converters and digital-to-analog converters in their flash memory-based FPGA fabric.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Most of the logic inside of an FPGA is synchronous circuitry that requires a clock signal.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] FPGAs contain dedicated global and regional routing networks for clock and reset, typically implemented as an H tree, so they can be delivered with minimal skew.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] FPGAs may contain analog phase-locked loop or delay-locked loop components to synthesize new clock frequencies and manage jitter.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Complex designs can use multiple clocks with different frequency and phase relationships, each forming separate clock domains.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] These clock signals can be generated locally by an oscillator or they can be recovered from a data stream.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Care must be taken when building clock domain crossing circuitry to avoid metastability.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Some FPGAs contain dual port RAM blocks that are capable of working with different clocks, aiding in the construction of building FIFOs and dual port buffers that bridge clock domains.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] To shrink the size and power consumption of FPGAs, vendors such as Tabula and Xilinx have introduced 3D or stacked architectures.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Following the introduction of its 28 nm 7-series FPGAs, Xilinx said that several of the highest-density parts in those FPGA product lines will be constructed using multiple dies in one package, employing technology developed for 3D construction and stacked-die assemblies.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Xilinx's approach stacks several (three or four) active FPGA dies side by side on a silicon interposer – a single piece of silicon that carries passive interconnect.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] The multi-die construction also allows different parts of the FPGA to be created with different process technologies, as the process requirements are different between the FPGA fabric itself and the very high speed 28 Gbit/s serial transceivers.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] An FPGA built in this way is called a *heterogeneous FPGA*.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Altera's heterogeneous approach involves using a single monolithic FPGA die and connecting other dies and technologies to the FPGA using Intel's embedded multi-die interconnect bridge (EMIB) technology.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] To define the behavior of the FPGA, the user provides a design in a hardware description language (HDL) or as a schematic design.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] The HDL form is more suited to work with large structures because it's possible to specify high-level functional behavior rather than drawing every piece by hand.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] However, schematic entry can allow for easier visualization of a design and its component modules.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Using an electronic design automation tool, a technology-mapped netlist is generated.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] The netlist can then be fit to the actual FPGA architecture using a process called *place and route*, usually performed by the FPGA company's proprietary place-and-route software.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] The user will validate the results using timing analysis, simulation, and other verification and validation techniques.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Once the design and validation process is complete, the binary file generated, typically using the FPGA vendor's proprietary software, is used to (re-)configure the FPGA.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] This file is transferred to the FPGA via a serial interface (JTAG) or to an external memory device such as an EEPROM.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] The most common HDLs are VHDL and Verilog.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] National Instruments' LabVIEW graphical programming language (sometimes referred to as *G*) has an FPGA add-in module available to target and program FPGA hardware.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Verilog was created to simplify the process, making HDL more robust and flexible.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Verilog has a C-like syntax, unlike VHDL which is based on Ada.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] To simplify the design of complex systems in FPGAs, there exist libraries of predefined complex functions and circuits that have been tested and optimized to speed up the design process.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] These predefined circuits are commonly called *intellectual property (IP) cores*, and are available from FPGA vendors and third-party IP suppliers.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] They are rarely free, and typically released under proprietary licenses.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Other predefined circuits are available from developer communities such as OpenCores (typically released under free and open source licenses such as the GPL, BSD or similar license).
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Such designs are known as open-source hardware.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] In a typical design flow, an FPGA application developer will simulate the design at multiple stages throughout the design process.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Initially, the RTL description in VHDL or Verilog is simulated by creating test benches to simulate the system and observe results.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Then, after the synthesis engine has mapped the design to a netlist, the netlist is translated to a gate-level description where simulation is repeated to confirm the synthesis proceeded without errors.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Finally, the design is laid out in the FPGA at which point propagation delay values can be back-annotated onto the netlist, and the simulation can be run again with these values.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] More recently, OpenCL (Open Computing Language) is being used by programmers to take advantage of the performance and power efficiencies that FPGAs provide.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] OpenCL allows programmers to develop code in the C programming language.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] For further information, see high-level synthesis and C to HDL.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Most FPGAs rely on an SRAM-based approach to be programmed.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] These FPGAs are in-system programmable and re-programmable, but require external boot devices.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] For example, flash memory or EEPROM devices may load contents into internal SRAM that controls routing and logic.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] In 2016, long-time industry rivals Xilinx (now part of AMD) and Altera were the FPGA market leaders.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] At that time, they controlled nearly 90 percent of the market.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Both Xilinx and Altera provide proprietary electronic design automation software for Windows and Linux (ISE/Vivado and Quartus) which enables engineers to design, analyze, simulate, and synthesize (compile) their designs.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] In March 2010, Tabula announced their FPGA technology that uses time-multiplexed logic and interconnect that claims potential cost savings for high-density applications.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] On March 24, 2015, Tabula officially shut down.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] On June 1, 2015, Intel announced it would acquire Altera for approximately US$16.7 billion and completed the acquisition on December 30, 2015.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] On October 27, 2020, AMD announced it would acquire Xilinx and completed the acquisition valued at about US$50 billion in February 2022.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] In February 2024 Altera became independent of Intel again.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] An FPGA can be used to solve any problem that is computable.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] FPGAs can be used to implement a soft microprocessor, such as the Xilinx MicroBlaze or Altera Nios II.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] But their advantage lies in that they are significantly faster for some applications because of their parallel nature and optimality in terms of the number of gates used for certain processes.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] FPGAs were originally introduced as competitors to complex programmable logic devices (CPLDs) to implement glue logic for printed circuit boards.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] As their size, capabilities, and speed increased, FPGAs took over additional functions to the point where some are now marketed as full systems on chips (SoCs).
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Particularly with the introduction of dedicated multipliers into FPGA architectures in the late 1990s, applications that had traditionally been the sole reserve of digital signal processors (DSPs) began to use FPGAs instead.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] The evolution of FPGAs has motivated an increase in the use of these devices, whose architecture allows the development of hardware solutions optimized for complex tasks, such as 3D MRI image segmentation, 3D discrete wavelet transform, tomographic image reconstruction, or PET/MRI systems.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] The developed solutions can perform intensive computation tasks with parallel processing, are dynamically reprogrammable, and have a low cost, all while meeting the hard real-time requirements associated with medical imaging.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Another trend in the use of FPGAs is hardware acceleration, where one can use the FPGA to accelerate certain parts of an algorithm and share part of the computation between the FPGA and a general-purpose processor.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] The search engine Bing is noted for adopting FPGA acceleration for its search algorithm in 2014.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] As of 2018, FPGAs are seeing increased use as AI accelerators including Microsoft's Project Catapult and for accelerating artificial neural networks for machine learning applications.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Originally, FPGAs were reserved for specific vertical applications where the volume of production is small.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] For these low-volume applications, the premium that companies pay in hardware cost per unit for a programmable chip is more affordable than the development resources spent on creating an ASIC.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Often a custom-made chip would be cheaper if made in larger quantities, but FPGAs may be chosen to quickly bring a product to market.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] By 2017, new cost and performance dynamics broadened the range of viable applications.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] FPGAs play a crucial role in modern military communications, especially in systems like the Joint Tactical Radio System (JTRS) and in devices from companies such as Thales and Harris Corporation.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Their flexibility and programmability make them ideal for military communications, offering customizable and secure signal processing.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] In the JTRS, used by the US military, FPGAs provide adaptability and real-time processing, crucial for meeting various communication standards and encryption methods.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Concerning hardware security, FPGAs have both advantages and disadvantages as compared to ASICs or secure microprocessors.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] FPGAs' flexibility makes malicious modifications during fabrication a lower risk.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Previously, for many FPGAs, the design bitstream was exposed while the FPGA loads it from external memory, typically during powerup.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] All major FPGA vendors now offer a spectrum of security solutions to designers, such as bitstream encryption and authentication.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] For example, Altera and Xilinx offer AES encryption (up to 256-bit) for bitstreams stored in an external flash memory.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Physical unclonable functions (PUFs) are integrated circuits that have their own unique signatures and can be used to secure FPGAs while taking up very little hardware space.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] FPGAs that store their configuration internally in nonvolatile flash memory, such as Microsemi's ProAsic 3 or Lattice's XP2 programmable devices, do not expose the bitstream and do not need encryption.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Customers wanting a higher guarantee of tamper resistance can use write-once, antifuse FPGAs from vendors such as Microsemi.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] With its Stratix 10 FPGAs and SoCs, Altera introduced a Secure Device Manager and physical unclonable functions to provide high levels of protection against physical attacks.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] In 2012, researchers Sergei Skorobogatov and Christopher Woods demonstrated that some FPGAs can be vulnerable to hostile intent.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] In 2020, a critical vulnerability (named Starbleed) was discovered in all Xilinx 7 series FPGAs that rendered bitstream encryption useless.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Xilinx did not produce a hardware revision.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Ultrascale and later devices, already on the market at the time, were not affected.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Historically, FPGAs have been slower, less energy efficient and generally achieved less functionality than their fixed ASIC counterparts.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] A study from 2006 showed that designs implemented on FPGAs need on average 40 times as much area, draw 12 times as much dynamic power, and run at one third the speed of corresponding ASIC implementations.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Advantages of FPGAs include the ability to reprogram equipment in the field to fix bugs or make other improvements.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Some FPGAs have the capability of partial re-configuration that lets one portion of the device be re-programmed while other portions continue running.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Other advantages may include shorter time to market and lower non-recurring engineering costs.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Vendors can also take a middle road via FPGA prototyping: developing their prototype hardware on FPGAs, but manufacturing their final version as an ASIC after the design has been committed.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] This is often also the case with new processor designs.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] The primary differences between CPLDs and FPGAs are architectural.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] A CPLD has a comparatively restrictive structure consisting of one or more programmable sum-of-products logic arrays feeding a relatively small number of clocked registers.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] As a result, CPLDs are less flexible but have the advantage of more predictable propagation delay.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] FPGA architectures, on the other hand, are dominated by interconnect.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] This makes them far more flexible but also far more complex to design for, or at least requiring more complex electronic design automation (EDA) software.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Another distinction between FPGAs and CPLDs is one of size, as FPGAs are usually much larger in terms of resources than CPLDs.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Typically only FPGAs contain more complex embedded functions such as adders, multipliers, memory, and serializer/deserializers.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Another common distinction is that CPLDs contain embedded flash memory to store their configuration, while FPGAs typically store their configuration in SRAM and require external non-volatile memory to initialize it on powerup.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] When a design requires simple instant-on, CPLDs are generally preferred.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] Sometimes both CPLDs and FPGAs are used in a single system design.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/field-programmable-gate-array] In those designs, CPLDs generally perform glue logic functions.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] To perform computing tasks more efficiently, generally one can invest time and money in improving the software, improving the hardware, or both.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] There are various approaches with advantages and disadvantages in terms of decreased latency, increased throughput, and reduced energy consumption.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] Typical advantages of focusing on software may include greater versatility, more rapid development, lower non-recurring engineering costs, heightened portability, and ease of updating features or patching bugs, at the cost of overhead to compute general operations.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] This hierarchy includes general-purpose processors such as CPUs, more specialized processors such as programmable shaders in a GPU, applications implemented on field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs), and fixed-function implemented on application-specific integrated circuits (ASICs).
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] Hardware acceleration is advantageous for performance, and practical when the functions are fixed, so updates are not as needed as in software solutions.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] With the advent of reprogrammable logic devices such as FPGAs, the restriction of hardware acceleration to fully fixed algorithms has eased since 2010, allowing hardware acceleration to be applied to problem domains requiring modification to algorithms and processing control flow.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] The disadvantage, however, is that in many open source projects, it requires proprietary libraries that not all vendors are keen to distribute or expose, making it difficult to integrate in such projects.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] Integrated circuits are designed to handle various operations on both analog and digital signals.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] In computing, digital signals are the most common and are typically represented as binary numbers.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] Computer hardware and software use this binary representation to perform computations.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] This is done by processing Boolean functions on the binary input, and then outputting the results for storage or further processing by other devices.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] Because all Turing machines can run any computable function, it is always possible to design custom hardware that performs the same function as a given piece of software.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] Conversely, software can always be used to emulate the function of a given piece of hardware.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] Custom hardware may offer higher performance per watt for the same functions that can be specified in software.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] Hardware description languages (HDLs) such as Verilog and VHDL can model the same semantics as software and synthesize the design into a netlist that can be programmed to an FPGA or composed into the logic gates of an ASIC.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] The vast majority of software-based computing occurs on machines implementing the von Neumann architecture, collectively known as stored-program computers.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] Computer programs are stored as data and executed by processors.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] Such processors must fetch and decode instructions, as well as load data operands from memory (as part of the instruction cycle), to execute the instructions constituting the software program.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] Relying on a common cache for code and data leads to the "von Neumann bottleneck", a fundamental limitation on the throughput of software on processors implementing the von Neumann architecture.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] Even in the modified Harvard architecture, where instructions and data have separate caches in the memory hierarchy, there is overhead to decoding instruction opcodes and multiplexing available execution units on a microprocessor or microcontroller, leading to low circuit utilization.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] Modern processors that provide simultaneous multithreading exploit under-utilization of available processor functional units and instruction level parallelism between different hardware threads.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] Hardware execution units do not in general rely on the von Neumann or modified Harvard architectures and do not need to perform the instruction fetch and decode steps of an instruction cycle and incur those stages' overhead.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] If needed calculations are specified in a register transfer level (RTL) hardware design, the time and circuit area costs that would be incurred by instruction fetch and decoding stages can be reclaimed and put to other uses.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] This reclamation saves time, power, and circuit area in computation.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] The reclaimed resources can be used for increased parallel computation, other functions, communication, or memory, as well as increased input/output capabilities.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] This comes at the cost of general-purpose utility.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] Custom hardware is limited in parallel processing capability only by the area and logic blocks available on the integrated circuit die.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] Therefore, hardware is much freer to offer massive parallelism than software on general-purpose processors, offering a possibility of implementing the parallel random-access machine (PRAM) model.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] It is common to build multicore and manycore processing units out of microprocessor IP core schematics on a single FPGA or ASIC.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] Similarly, specialized functional units can be composed in parallel, as in digital signal processing, without being embedded in a processor IP core.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] Therefore, hardware acceleration is often employed for repetitive, fixed tasks involving little conditional branching, especially on large amounts of data.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] This is how Nvidia's CUDA line of GPUs are implemented.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] As device mobility has increased, new metrics have been developed that measure the relative performance of specific acceleration protocols, considering characteristics such as physical hardware dimensions, power consumption, and operations throughput.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] These can be summarized into three categories: task efficiency, implementation efficiency, and flexibility.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] Appropriate metrics consider the area of the hardware along with both the corresponding operations throughput and energy consumed.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] The hardware that performs the acceleration may be part of a general-purpose CPU, or a separate unit called a hardware accelerator, though they are usually referred to with a more specific term, such as 3D accelerator, or cryptographic accelerator.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] Traditionally, processors were sequential (instructions are executed one by one), and were designed to run general-purpose algorithms controlled by instruction fetch (for example, moving temporary results to and from a register file).
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] Hardware accelerators improve the execution of a specific algorithm by allowing greater concurrency, having specific datapaths for their temporary variables, and reducing the overhead of instruction control in the fetch-decode-execute cycle.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] Modern processors are multi-core and often feature parallel "single-instruction; multiple data" (SIMD) units.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] Such units can be integrated withint the CPU or offered by additional components as the AMD AI engines.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] Even so, hardware acceleration still yields benefits.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] Hardware acceleration is suitable for any computation-intensive algorithm that is executed frequently in a task or program.
[src:hardware-accelerator-design/hardware-acceleration] Depending upon the granularity, hardware acceleration can vary from a small functional unit to a large functional block (like motion estimation in MPEG-2).
